<document xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml">
  <title>The Matrix Exponential as a Limit of Powers</title>

  <metadata><md:content-id>undefined</md:content-id><md:title/><md:uuid>842926d3-42b0-41e6-8c22-40e05ea6fa60</md:uuid>
</metadata>

  <content>
    <para id="para1">
      You may recall from Calculus that for any numbers
      <m:math><m:ci>a</m:ci></m:math> and
      <m:math><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:math> one may achieve
      <m:math>
	<m:apply>
	  <m:exp/>
	  <m:apply>
	    <m:times/>
	    <m:ci>a</m:ci>
	    <m:ci>t</m:ci>
	  </m:apply>
	</m:apply>
      </m:math> via 
      
      <equation id="eq1">
	<m:math display="block">
	  <m:apply>
	    <m:eq/>
	    <m:apply>
	      <m:exp/>
	      <m:apply>
		<m:times/>
		<m:ci>a</m:ci>
		<m:ci>t</m:ci>
	      </m:apply>
	    </m:apply>
	    <m:apply>
	      <m:limit/>
	      <m:bvar><m:ci>k</m:ci></m:bvar>
	      <m:lowlimit><m:infinity/></m:lowlimit>
	      <m:apply>
		<m:power/>
		<m:apply>
		  <m:plus/>
		  <m:cn>1</m:cn>
		  <m:apply>
		    <m:divide/>
		    <m:apply>
		      <m:times/>
		      <m:ci>a</m:ci>
		      <m:ci>t</m:ci>
		    </m:apply>
		    <m:ci>k</m:ci>
		  </m:apply>
		</m:apply>
		<m:ci>k</m:ci>
	      </m:apply>
	    </m:apply>
	  </m:apply>
	</m:math>
      </equation>

      The natural matrix definition is therefore 
      
      <equation id="eq2">
	<m:math display="block">
	  <m:apply>
	    <m:eq/>
	    <m:apply>
	      <m:exp/>
	      <m:apply>
		<m:times/>
		<m:ci>A</m:ci>
		<m:ci>t</m:ci>
	      </m:apply>
	    </m:apply>
	    <m:apply>
	      <m:limit/>
	      <m:bvar><m:ci>k</m:ci></m:bvar>
	      <m:lowlimit><m:infinity/></m:lowlimit>
	      <m:apply>
		<m:power/>
		<m:apply>
		  <m:plus/>
		  <m:ci>I</m:ci>
		  <m:apply>
		    <m:divide/>
		    <m:apply>
		      <m:times/>
		      <m:ci>A</m:ci>
		      <m:ci>t</m:ci>
		    </m:apply>
		    <m:ci>k</m:ci>
		  </m:apply>
		</m:apply>
		<m:ci>k</m:ci>
	      </m:apply>
	    </m:apply>
	  </m:apply>
	</m:math>
      </equation>

      where <m:math><m:ci>I</m:ci></m:math> is the n-by-n identity
      matrix. </para>

    <example id="example1">
      <para id="ex1para1">
	The easiest case is the diagonal case, <foreign>e.g.</foreign>, 
	
	<m:math display="block">
	  <m:apply>
	    <m:eq/>
	    <m:ci>A</m:ci>
	    <m:matrix>
	      <m:matrixrow>
		<m:cn>1</m:cn>
		<m:cn>0</m:cn>
	      </m:matrixrow>
	      <m:matrixrow>
		<m:cn>0</m:cn>
		<m:cn>2</m:cn>
	      </m:matrixrow>
	    </m:matrix>
	  </m:apply>
	</m:math> 

	for then

	<m:math display="block">
	  <m:apply>
	    <m:eq/>
	    <m:apply>
	      <m:power/>
	      <m:apply>
		<m:plus/>
		<m:ci>I</m:ci>
		<m:apply>
		  <m:divide/>
		  <m:apply>
		    <m:times/>
		    <m:ci>A</m:ci>
		    <m:ci>t</m:ci>
		  </m:apply>
		  <m:ci>k</m:ci>
		</m:apply>
	      </m:apply>
	      <m:ci>k</m:ci>
	    </m:apply>
	    <m:matrix>
	      <m:matrixrow>
		<m:apply>
		  <m:power/>
		  <m:apply>
		    <m:plus/>
		    <m:cn>1</m:cn>
		    <m:apply>
		      <m:divide/>
		      <m:ci>t</m:ci>
		      <m:ci>k</m:ci>
		    </m:apply>
		  </m:apply>
		  <m:ci>k</m:ci>
		</m:apply>
		<m:cn>0</m:cn>
	      </m:matrixrow>
	      <m:matrixrow>
		<m:cn>0</m:cn>
		<m:apply>
		  <m:power/>
		  <m:apply>
		    <m:plus/>
		    <m:cn>1</m:cn>
		    <m:apply>
		      <m:divide/>
		      <m:apply>
			<m:times/>
			<m:cn>2</m:cn>
			<m:ci>t</m:ci>
		      </m:apply>
		      <m:ci>k</m:ci>
		    </m:apply>
		  </m:apply>
		  <m:ci>k</m:ci>
		</m:apply>
	      </m:matrixrow>
	    </m:matrix>
	  </m:apply>
	</m:math>

	and so (recalling <link target-id="eq1" strength="3"/> above)

	<m:math display="block">
	  <m:apply>
	    <m:eq/>
	    <m:apply>
	      <m:exp/>
	      <m:apply>
		<m:times/>
		<m:ci>A</m:ci>
		<m:ci>t</m:ci>
	      </m:apply>
	    </m:apply>
	    <m:matrix>
	      <m:matrixrow>
		<m:apply>
		  <m:exp/>
		  <m:ci>t</m:ci>
		</m:apply>
		<m:cn>0</m:cn>
	      </m:matrixrow>
	      <m:matrixrow>
		<m:cn>0</m:cn>
		<m:apply>
		  <m:exp/>
		  <m:apply>
		    <m:times/>
		    <m:cn>2</m:cn>
		    <m:ci>t</m:ci>
		  </m:apply>
		</m:apply>
	      </m:matrixrow>
	    </m:matrix>
	  </m:apply>
	</m:math>
	
	Note that this is <term>NOT</term> the exponential of each
	element of <m:math><m:ci>A</m:ci></m:math>. </para>
    </example>


    <example id="example2">
      <para id="ex2para1">
	As a concrete example let us suppose 

